## Redgate Flyway

Flyway works differently then Bytebase in that it doesn’t have a centralized view, the tool is provided in a desktop app, cli and an API version which is then integrated into an existing CI like Github CI. The process works similarly to Bytebase GitOps, in that it follows naming conventions for running scripts in order, and it creates a metadata table to track changes and has a revision history this is a more straightforward less complex way of handling history, but it lacks programmatical control in the history that you can get with Liquibase programmatic control. It has different offerings:

- Free
- Teams
- Enterprise

Naturally they differ in the functionalities. The free versions give just the bare minimum command to work the migrations, while the Team provide features like:

- dry run,
- undo migration scripts
- cherry pick
- etc.

while Enterprise provides more features which some of them are:

- drift detection
- change reports
- data comparison

Take in consideration that as are mostly for Oracle and MSSQL.

Also, Flyway supports repeatable migration scripts prefixed with "R_\_". These scripts are useful for managing database objects like views that can be recreated without affecting data, which will help devs and QA people because there is a lot of back forth for these kinds of scripts.
